First let's show the image and its transform in the Fourier domain¶

In [5]:
import cv2
import numpy as np
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

#loading the image
img = cv2.imread('barbara.jpg',0)

#performing the fft and using the fftshift function to shift the zero-frequency component to the center of the array
f = np.fft.fft2(img)
fshift = np.fft.fftshift(f)
magnitude_spectrum = 20*np.log(np.abs(fshift))

#ploting the image and its magnitude spectrum
fig= plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))
plt.subplot(121),plt.imshow(img, cmap = 'gray')
plt.title('Original image'), plt.xticks([]), plt.yticks([])
plt.subplot(122),plt.imshow(magnitude_spectrum, cmap = 'gray')
plt.title('Magnitude Spectrum in the Fourier domain'), plt.xticks([]), plt.yticks([])
plt.show()

Resizing (size divided by 2) using bi-linear interpolation¶

In [8]:

plt.title('Resized image using subsampling in space domain')
plt.imshow(small, cmap = 'gray')
Out[8]:
<matplotlib.image.AxesImage at 0x7f4eeba62470>

When using a linear interpolation to subsample, there is an aliasing effect due to the fact that the sampling frequency is not high enough compared to the max frequency of the image ( observed on the stripes of Barbara's trousers). Instead of vertical lines on the trousers, we have horizontal or diagonal stripes, sometimes square shapes. Using Shannons Sampling Theorem, the minimum sampling should be such that : $ f_s \geq 2 f_{max}$

Resizing (size divided by 2) in the Fourier domain¶

Here the idea is to subsample by having an image that is 2 times smaller in the Fourier domain. What we do is to keep the center of the image because the high frequencies are situated on the edges, so we have a low-pass filter

In [9]:
def crop_center(img,cropx,cropy):
    y,x = img.shape
    startx = x//2-(cropx//2)
    starty = y//2-(cropy//2)    
    return img[starty:starty+cropy,startx:startx+cropx]

small_fft = crop_center(fshift , 256 , 256)
In [10]:
f_ishift = np.fft.ifftshift(small_fft)
img_back = np.fft.ifft2(f_ishift)
img_back = np.abs(img_back)


fig= plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))

plt.title('Resized image by cropping edges in the Fourier domain')
plt.imshow(img_back , cmap = 'gray')
Out[10]:
<matplotlib.image.AxesImage at 0x7f4eeb9cd9e8>

The effect here is not the same as with a linear interpolation. As the high frequencies are removed, the contrast is lower and the right part of the trousers for instance looks uniform.

</b>

x2 zoom using bilinear interpolation¶

When upsampling using a bilinear interpolation, the principle is to make an average or the surrounding neighbors of the new pixels that we will have. Therefore, the image seems smoother

In [87]:
bilinear_img = cv2.resize(img,None, fx = 2, fy = 2, interpolation = cv2.INTER_LINEAR)

x2 zoom using bilinear zero-padding in the Fourier domain¶

Here we do a sinc interpolation, which in the Fourier domain consists in having an image that is 2 times larger with zero padding because the transform of a window is sinc. The frequencies, which are the low frequencies are kept in the center.

</b>

In [89]:
def zero_padding(img, xsize , ysize):

    zero_padd = np.zeros((xsize*2 , ysize*2))
    zero_padd[ int(xsize/2) : int(3/2 * xsize), int(ysize/2) : int(3/2 * ysize)] = img
    return zero_padd
In [107]:
zero_padd_fft = np.pad(fshift, [256 , 256], mode='constant')

plt.imshow(img_back , cmap = 'gray')
Out[119]:
<matplotlib.image.AxesImage at 0x7f8aab71a9b0>

When we take the Fourier transform of the image , we treat each row of the image as a periodic signal whose period is the width of the image, and the same is true for the columns. This reattaches grey levels from opposite edges of the image side by side, which introduces a strong discontinuity, which corresponds, in the Fourier plane, to very high frequencies. However, the high frequencies of the zoomed image, being unknown, are taken equal to zero which makes characteristic oscillations appear on the edges of the image, and generally on all strong discontinuities.
